    "updated_at": "2026-03-02T09:55:56Z",
    "body": "I see two main paths for implementing this in `QuantumCircuitData`'s `FromPyObject` implementation:\n\n1.  We explicitly check if the object is an instance of `BlueprintCircuit`. Since calling back into Python to import this class on every circuit conversion could add overhead, would you prefer I cache the `BlueprintCircuit` type in Rust (e.g., during module initialization) to make the `isinstance` check fast?\n2. Instead of a strict type check, we check for a lazy-initialization marker before grabbing `_data`. For example, checking if the object has the `_is_built` attribute via `ob.getattr(\"_is_built\")`. If it exists and is `False`, we force it to build (e.g., by calling `.data` or `._build()`) before extracting `_data`.\n\nis there a preference? Or is there another existing pattern in the Rust bindings for handling lazy Python objects that I should follow here?",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "pin": null,
